<DOC><DOCNO>  ZF108-834-724  </DOCNO><DOCID>08 834 724.andO;</DOCID><JOURNAL>Computerworld  Sept 10 1990 v24 n37 p66(1).andM;</JOURNAL><TITLE>A jewel in the on-line service. (Jewel Foodstores and Prodigy)</TITLE><AUTHOR>Fitzgerald, Michael.andM;</AUTHOR><TEXT><ABSTRACT>American Stores Co's Jewel Foodstores division has joined withPeapod Delivery Systems to create a computerized grocery servicewhere customers can order their groceries on-line and have themdelivered to their homes.andP;  The new joint venture will offercompetition for Prodigy, an IBM, Sears, Roebuck and Co jointventure, which has already solicited Dominick's Finer Foodsgrocery store.andP;  Jewel chose Peapod Delivery over Prodigy becauseit was more affordable for the consumer and offered menus thatwere faster and gave more detail.andP;  The system, which pulls productinformation on about 12,000 items from Jewel mainframe computers,allows shoppers to create a personalized shopping list of up to 50items and browse through computerized aisles.andP;  Peapod customerspay an initial fee of $15 for the software and an annualmembership fee of $35.andM;</ABSTRACT></TEXT><DESCRIPT>Company:   American Stores Co. (contracts)Prodigy Systems Inc. (services)Peapod Delivery Systems Inc. (contracts).andO;Ticker:    ASC.andO;Topic:     Food IndustryOn-Line Transaction ProcessingContracts.andM;</DESCRIPT></DOC>